<p>
On the other hand, a sequence of elements from an metric space <img src=3D"=
https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Limit/Inline18.svg" class=3D=
"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=
=3D"15" height=3D"21" alt=3D"X"> may have several - even infinitely many - =
different limits
 provided that <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/L=
imit/Inline19.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-wid=
th:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"15" height=3D"21" alt=3D"X">
 is equipped with a topology which fails to be <a href=3D"https://mathworld=
.wolfram.com/T2-Space.html">T2</a>. One
 reads the expression in (1) as "the limit as <img src=3D"https://mathworld=
.wolfram.com/images/equations/Limit/Inline20.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" s=
tyle=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"=
21" alt=3D"n"> approaches infinity of <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram=
.com/images/equations/Limit/Inline21.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"=
max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"16" height=3D"21" alt=
=3D"x_n"> is <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Lim=
it/Inline22.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width=
:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"11" height=3D"21" alt=3D"L">."
</p>
<p>
The topological notion of convergence can be rewritten to accommodate a wid=
er array of topological spaces <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/im=
ages/equations/Limit/Inline23.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-hei=
ght:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"15" height=3D"21" alt=3D"X">
 by utilizing the language of <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Net.=
html">nets</a>. In particular, if <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com=
/images/equations/Limit/Inline24.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-=
height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"56" height=3D"21" alt=3D"=
x=3D{x_i}"> is a net from a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Direct=
edSet.html">directed
 set</a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Limit/I=
nline25.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100=
%" border=3D"0" width=3D"8" height=3D"21" alt=3D"I"> into <img src=3D"https=
://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Limit/Inline26.svg" class=3D"inli=
neformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"1=
5" height=3D"21" alt=3D"X">, then an element <img src=3D"https://mathworld.=
wolfram.com/images/equations/Limit/Inline27.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" st=
yle=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"43" height=3D"=
21" alt=3D"x in X"> is said to be the limit of <img src=3D"https://mathworl=
d.wolfram.com/images/equations/Limit/Inline28.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" =
style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D=
"21" alt=3D"x"> if and only if for every neighborhood <img src=3D"https://m=
athworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Limit/Inline29.svg" class=3D"inlinefo=
rmula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"15" h=
eight=3D"21" alt=3D"U"> of <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images=
/equations/Limit/Inline30.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:=
100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"x">,
 <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Limit/Inline31.=
svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" borde=
r=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"x"> is eventually in <img src=3D"h=
ttps://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Limit/Inline32.svg" class=3D"=
inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=
=3D"15" height=3D"21" alt=3D"U">, i.e., if there exists an <img src=3D"http=
s://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Limit/Inline33.svg" class=3D"inl=
ineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"=
32" height=3D"21" alt=3D"i in I"> so that, for every <img src=3D"https://ma=
thworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Limit/Inline34.svg" class=3D"inlinefor=
mula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"35" he=
ight=3D"21" alt=3D"j in I"> with <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/=
images/equations/Limit/Inline35.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-h=
eight:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"32" height=3D"21" alt=3D"j=
&gt;=3Di">, the point <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equa=
tions/Limit/Inline36.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;=
max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"16" height=3D"24" alt=3D"x_j"> lies i=
n <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Limit/Inline37=
.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" bord=
er=3D"0" width=3D"15" height=3D"21" alt=3D"U">. This notion is particularly=
 well-purposed for topological
