<p>
The expression in (2) is read "the limit as <img src=3D"https://mathworld.w=
olfram.com/images/equations/Limit/Inline58.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" sty=
le=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"8" height=3D"21=
" alt=3D"z"> approaches <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/eq=
uations/Limit/Inline59.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100=
%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"a"> from th=
e left / from below" or "the limit as <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram=
.com/images/equations/Limit/Inline60.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"=
max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"8" height=3D"21" alt=
=3D"z"> increases to <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equat=
ions/Limit/Inline61.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;m=
ax-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"a">," while (3=
) is read "the limit as <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/eq=
uations/Limit/Inline62.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100=
%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"8" height=3D"21" alt=3D"z"> approac=
hes <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Limit/Inline=
63.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" bo=
rder=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"a"> from the right / from above=
" or "the limit as <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equatio=
ns/Limit/Inline64.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max=
-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"8" height=3D"21" alt=3D"z"> decreases to=
 <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Limit/Inline65.=
svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" borde=
r=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"a">." In (4), one simply refers to=
 "the limit as <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/L=
imit/Inline66.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-wid=
th:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"8" height=3D"21" alt=3D"z"> approaches <img =
src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Limit/Inline67.svg" c=
lass=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0=
" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"a">."
</p>
<p>
Limits are implemented in the <a href=3D"http://www.wolfram.com/language/">=
Wolfram Language</a> as <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wolfram.com/languag=
e/ref/Limit.html">Limit</a></tt>[<i>f</i>,
 <i>x</i><tt>-&gt; </tt><i>x0</i>]. This command also takes options <tt>Dir=
ection</tt>
 (which can be set to any complex direction, including for example <img src=
=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Limit/Inline68.svg" clas=
s=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" w=
idth=3D"21" height=3D"21" alt=3D"+1">, <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfra=
m.com/images/equations/Limit/Inline69.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D=
"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"21" height=3D"21" al=
t=3D"-1">,
 <tt>I</tt>, and <tt>-I</tt>), and <tt>Analytic</tt>, which computes symbol=
ic limits
 for functions.
</p>
<p>
Note that the function definition of limit can be thought of as a natural g=
eneralization of the sequence definition due to the fact that a sequence <i=
mg src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Limit/Inline70.svg=
" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=
=3D"0" width=3D"69" height=3D"21" alt=3D"x_1,x_2,..."> in a topological spa=
ce <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Limit/Inline7=
1.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" bor=
der=3D"0" width=3D"15" height=3D"21" alt=3D"X"> is nothing more than a func=
tion <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Limit/Inlin=
e72.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" b=
order=3D"0" width=3D"71" height=3D"21" alt=3D"g:N-&gt;X"> mapping <img src=
=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Limit/Inline73.svg" clas=
