<p>
All of the above notions can be generalized even further by utilizing the l=
anguage of <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Ultrafilter.html">ultra=
filters</a>. In particular, if <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/im=
ages/equations/Limit/Inline95.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-hei=
ght:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"49" height=3D"21" alt=3D"(X,=
T)"> is a topological space and if <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.co=
m/images/equations/Limit/Inline96.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max=
-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"16" height=3D"21" alt=3D=
"U"> is an ultrafilter on <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/=
equations/Limit/Inline97.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:1=
00%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"15" height=3D"21" alt=3D"X">, the=
n an element <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Lim=
it/Inline98.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width=
:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"43" height=3D"21" alt=3D"x in X"> is said to b=
e a limit of <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Lim=
it/Inline99.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width=
:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"16" height=3D"21" alt=3D"U"> if every neighbor=
hood of <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Limit/In=
line100.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100=
%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"x"> belongs to <img src=3D=
"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Limit/Inline101.svg" class=
=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" wi=
dth=3D"16" height=3D"21" alt=3D"U">. Several authors have defined similar i=
deas relative to <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Filter.html">filt=
ers</a> as well (Stadler and Stadler 2002).
</p>
